    'body' => 'That big batch of copyright messages had two problems:
The SJG quotes came out of a wordprocessor with formatting codes still 
included.
The messages arrived out of order in the digest. I\'d advise putting the 
whole thing (with the SJG stuff strtipped of weird characters and 
formatting) on one of the traveller ftp or WWW sites.

On to more positive notes.

I so very rarely see a well documented post on the \'Net. The references 
from FASA and Chaosium provide a nominal statement of copyright, without 
severe restrictions. All they want is to remind people who actually made 
the game discussed. They are required to do that, on an active basis to 
maintain the copyright. If the public refuses a company could very easily 
lose a big batch of copyrights with attendant loss of control over 
quality of materials. So follow the rules, in this case it is beneficial.

The Steve Jackson Game computer software license is a different kettle of 
fish because it assumes a financial responsibility on the programmers 
part. But if you are selling things, that\'s business. Notice the free 
license for free-ware and PD software. However, all of this could be very 
different if SJG was selling its own software.

I do not believe that such copyright statements could be required to 
aplly to private correspondence that is not open to the public. I haven\'t 
actually met any of the other people on this list, but I consider myself 
to be a party to a \'personal\' discussion with you all. I believe that a 
copyright notice on a private letter is silly and I don\'t see that the 
fact that it was sent to more than one stranger makes a difference. 

On the other hand it is clear that files on the ftp and WWW sites should 
include a copyright statement. At the end for a file available for ftp; 
on the title page of a web page or ftp site directory. Also, bundles of 
private messages in the archives would need ONE copyright notice at the 
end, just like anything else, because they are publicly available in the 
archive and are hence being \'distributed\'.



Needless to say I am not a lawyer, nor are these respectable legal 
opinions. Actually, I probably _do_ have to say that.

